text: pubs.acs.org/acschemicalbiology Identiﬁcation of a C‑Glycosyltransferase Involved in Medermycin Biosynthesis Xiaofeng Cai, Takaaki Taguchi, Huili Wang, Megumi Yuki, Megumi Tanaka, Kai Gong, Jinghua Xu, Yiming Zhao, Koji Ichinose,* and Aiying Li* ABSTRACT: C-Glycosylation in the biosynthesis of bioactive natural products is quite unique, which has not been studied well. Medermycin, as an antitumor agent in the family of pyranonaphthoquinone antibiotics, is featured with unique C-glycosylation. Here, a new C-glycosyltransferase (C-GT) Med-8 was identiﬁed to be essential for the biosynthesis of medermycin, as the ﬁrst example of C-GT to recognize a rare deoxyaminosugar (angolosamine). med-8 and six genes (med-14, -15, -16, -17, -18, and -20 located in the medermycin biosynthetic gene cluster) predicted for the biosynthesis of angolosamine were proved to be functional and suﬃcient for C-glycosylation. A C-glycosylation cassette composed of these seven genes could convert a proposed substrate into a C-glycosylated product. In conclusion, these genes involved in the C-glycosylation of medermycin were functionally identiﬁed and biosynthetically engineered, and they provided the possibility of producing new C-glycosylated compounds.

Glycosylation is widely distributed in the biosynthetic pathways of valuable glycosidic natural products as a key tailoring modiﬁcation and contributes to the structural and biological activity diversiﬁcation of these therapeutically important compounds.1,2 The attachment of sugar moieties to aglycones is usually mediated by diﬀerent glycosyltrans- ferases (GTs), which catalyze four types of glycosylation: O-, N-, C-, and S-type.3−7 C-Glycosylation is a unique phenom- enon in nature. Only a small number of biologically important natural products are C-glycosides, including some members in families of pluramycins, pyranonaphthoquinones (PNQs), salmochelins, angucyclines, and some ﬂavones (Figure S1).1,3,8−13 The regio- and stereospeciﬁc attachment of a nucleotide diphosphate (NDP)-activated donor (sugar moi- ety) determines the bioactivities of these valuable antimicrobial and anticancer compounds. Unlike the CC-O-C linkage, C-C glycosidic bonds are more stable against acid hydrolysis and glycosidase degradation, making these compounds particularly interesting as potential therapeutic drug candidates.11 Medermycin (MED, 1) (Figure 1) (also known as is a Streptomyces-derived C-glycosylated Cite This: ACS Chem. compound in the family of PNQs (also benzoisochromane- quinones (BIQs)).14−16 It displays strong antitumor activity as a novel allosteric inhibitor against a serine/threonine kinase AKT that plays a central role in human malignancy.17−19 MED 1 is also well-known for the ﬁrst hybrid antibiotic produced by a combinatorial biosynthesis through combining the bio- synthetic pathways of MED 1 and actinorhodin (ACT, 2) (Figure 1) from S. coelicolor A3(2), another extensively studied member of the PNQ family.20 A comparative analysis of the entire med and act biosynthetic gene clusters reveals that MED 1 and ACT 2 share an identical polyketide-derived earlier pathway, resulting in a common bicyclic intermediate. This intermediate undergoes the stereo- speciﬁc reduction at C-3 to aﬀord 4-dihydro-9-hydroxy-1- Received: March 28, 2021 Accepted: May 21, 2021 Published: June 3, 2021 *sı Supporting Information https://doi.org/10.1021/acschembio.1c00227 ACS Chem. A common intermediate, (S)-DNPA 3, is hydroxylated at C-6 by a two- component ﬂavin-dependent monooxygenase system Med-7/Med-1314,19−21 or ActVA-5/ActVB,22−24 and this is followed by an auto-oxidization to aﬀord DHK 6, further to KAL 4. Synthesis of NDP-ANG 5 from glucose by six ANG med genes and transfer into C-10 of KAL 4 by Med-8 were proposed to occur in the last step in the MED 1 pathway.14,20−22,24,28

methyl-10-oxo-3-H-naphtho-[2,3-c]-pyran-3-(S)-acetic acid ((S)-DNPA, 3) (Figure 1).14,19,21−26 The subsequent oxygen- ation step at C-6 produces a trihydroxynapththalene derivative sitting at the biosynthetic branch point leading to either MED 1 or ACT 2. Of particular interest, biosynthesis of MED 1 invovles a C-glycosylation of an aromatic polyketide pyranonaphthoquinone skeleton, kalafungin (KAL, 4), with a rare deoxyaminosugar, D-angolosamine (ANG) (Figure 1).27−29 Biosynthetic enzymes for a nucleotide diphosphate (NDP)- sugar and glycosyltransferase (GT) are indispensable for conventional glycosylation in natural products.1,3,30−32 The med cluster sp. AM-7161 (AM-7161) contains six genes (the ANG genes: med-14, -15, -16, -17, -18, and -20), the deduced functions of which lead to a plausible route to form NDP-ANG 5 (Figure 1).14 A single GT gene, med-8, is also present in the med cluster as the closest homologue to urdGT2 encoding a C-GT for an antitumor antibiotic urdamycin (URD) (Figure S1).33 It allows us to pubs.acs.org/acschemicalbiology hypothesize that Med-8 may catalyze the formation of a C−C bond between NDP-ANG 5 and KAL 4 (Figure 1).14,15

Both MED 1 and KAL 4 possess antitumor activity as inhibitors of AKT, and their biosyntheses are controlled by med gene cluster.14,29 C-Glycosylation is the only structural diﬀerence between MED 1 and KAL 4. Of great interest is that MED 1 has a stronger antitumor activity than KAL 4 by a twofold increase in the half-maximal inhibitory concentration (IC50) inhibiting AKT,17,18 implying signiﬁcant contributions of glycosylation in MED 1 to its inhibition of many types of human carcinogenesis. The present studies aim to oﬀer initial insights into a C- glycosylation in the biosynthesis of MED 1. Our data demonstrate that med-8 plays an essential role in the sugar transfer during MED 1 biosynthesis. Moreover, our engineered coexpression system composed of med-8 and six ANG genes is functional as a C-glycosylation cassette to synthesize and transfer the ANG moiety to its proposed substrate. https://doi.org/10.1021/acschembio.1c00227 ACS Chem. Med-8 Phylogenetically Belongs to the C-GT Family. To ﬁnd out the evolutionary relationship between Med-8 and other microbial GTs, we constructed a phylogenetic tree using amino sequences of Med-8 and its homologues that are GTs involved in the biosynthesis of other microbial natural products. As shown in Figure 2A, all proposed C-GTs are grouped distinctly into a subfamily, exempliﬁed by UrdGT2 for urdamycin/angucycline, SimB7 for simocycnone/angucycline, Gra-ORF14 for granaticin/pyranonaphthoquinone, GilGT for gilvocarcin/angucycline, and HedL for hedamycin/angucy- cline, besides Med-8. One exception in this subfamily is LanGT2 (as O-GT), which possesses a high identity (53%) with UrdGT2. Next, sequence alignment between Med-8 and other GTs (Figure S2) showed that three types of GTs are featured with a pubs.acs.org/acschemicalbiology highly conserved glycine-rich motif (282HHGGGVTG289 for Med-8) at their C-terminus proposed for donor binding and another conserved glycine-rich motif (44TGVGLPG50 for Med- 8) at the N-terminus proposed for acceptor binding. Two strictly conserved residue sites (D138 and P298 in Med-8, D137, and P301 in UrdGT2) in all C-GTs (Figure 2) are located in the proposed catalytic center.35−38

Additionally, the substitution of D298 in UrdGT2 (corre- sponding to D301 in the C-terminal of Med-8) abolished completely the activity of UrdGT2. It is also highlighted that the potential conserved catalytic base Asp restricted to O-GTs was randomly substituted in C-GT (I307 for Med-8) and N-GT, implying that this potential base residue might determine the speciﬁcity for C-glycosylation. The native producing strain AM-7161 produces MED 1, KAL 4, and DHK 6.29 In CH999/pIK340, an accumulation of MED 1 can be detected.14 The host CH999 did not produce any PNQ-related compounds, as a negative control. In the med-8-deﬁcient strain CH999/pHSL3, the production of MED 1 was completely abolished, and a PNQ-aglycone KAL 4 and related metabolites DHK 6, 4R-AcCys-DHK 7, and 4S-AcCys-DHK 8 were accumulated (Figure 5 for their structures).22−25,28 In the complementary strain CH999/(pHSL3+pHSL5), the production of MED 1 was restored at the presence of med-8. of this site abolished completely the activity of this enzyme (Figure S2).34

In addition, an active-site loop containing 10 residues in the N-terminal of Med-8 was found to be highly homologous to that in UrdGT2. This loop in LandGT2 was proposed to adopt a highly ﬂexible conformation, and substitutions using it converted LandGT2 into a C-GT.35,36 An exchange of active- site motifs also showed a remarkable change in glycosidic bond-type speciﬁcity between PcO-GT and OsC-GT, such as the I117-D118 dyad in PcO-GT (D120-I121 in OsC-GT). We indeed found the similar dyad V172-D173 in the sequence of Med-8, corresponding to I171-D172 in UrdGT2 (Figure S2).37,38 Thus, it is necessary to conﬁrm if these conserved residues or motifs are essential for the enzymatic activity of Med-8 in the future. Further homology modeling of Med-8 revealed that Med-8 belongs to the GT-B superfamily and likely possesses the similar fold UrdGT2 (PDB code: 2P6P) (Figure 2B and Figure pubs.acs.org/acschemicalbiology S2),37 implying its C-glycosylation role in the MED 1 biosynthesis, similar to that of UrdGT2 in the urdamycin pathway.

Med-8 is Essential in the Biosynthesis of MED 1. To examine the role of Med-8, a knockout of the med-8 gene was conducted to verify its involvement in the production of MED 1. Initially, a suicide plasmid was created for the knockout of med-8, but it failed to be introduced into the wild-type strain AM-7161. Instead, pIK340, an integrative plasmid carrying the entire med cluster, was proved to produce MED 1 in the act- gene-cluster-deﬁcient strain S. coelicolor CH999 (CH999/ pIK340).14,29 Therefore, an in-frame deletion of med-8 (Δmed- 8) was created on pIK340, generating a derivative plasmid pHSL3, followed by an introduction into CH999. The recombinant CH999 carrying pHSL3 (CH999/pHSL3) showed a diﬀerent pigmentation from either CH999/pIK340 or AM-7161, when grown on the agar plates (Figure 3A), possibly resulting from the deletion of med-8. these recombinant strains were separately cultivated in liquid cultures, the resulting culture supernatants of which were directly analyzed by liquid chromatography/electrospray ionization high-resolution mass spectrometry (LC/ESI- HRMS) (Figure 3B). The results showed that MED 1 was not detected in the engineered med-cluster-containing strain CH999/pHSL3 (namely, med-8-deﬁcient strain) in contrast to that in the CH999/pIK340 strain (equivalent to the wide-type strain) (Figure 3B and Figure S3). To further conﬁrm the role of med-8 in the biosynthesis of MED 1, the expression plasmid pHSL5 harboring a full-length med-8 was constructed, in which the expression of Med-8 was controlled by a constitutive ermE* promoter.39 Then pHSL5 was introduced into the deﬁcient strain (CH999/pHSL3) for eﬃcient expression of Med-8 under the ermE* promoter (Figure 3B).39 As shown in Figure 3A, CH999/(pHSL3+pHSL5) (namely, a complemen- tary strain) cultivated on the solid medium showed a brown pigmentation, apparently diﬀerent from the deﬁcient strain CH999/pHSL3. An LC/MS analysis of the liquid culture from the production of CH999/(pHSL3+pHSL5) showed that MED 1 was restored in the presence of med-8 (Figure 3B). The fact that the restored strain exhibited an apparent less MED productivity would be attributed to the med-8 expression system (pHSL5), which is diﬀerent from that of a native med-8 within the potential polycistronic transcriptional unit com- pubs.acs.org/acschemicalbiology posed of a pathway speciﬁc activator, med-11 and the other two genes (Figure 4A).14

Accumulation of Intermediates or Shunt Products in the Mutant Strain. In addition to the inability of the med-8- deﬁcient strain CH999/pHSL3 to produce MED 1, is noteworthy that this strain accumulated several compounds, indicated by several peaks in the high-performance liquid chromatography (HPLC) proﬁle, in marked contrast to the wild-type strain (CH999/pIK340). shown that compound 4 detected in a comparable amount in the mutant strain CH999/pHSL3 was conﬁrmed to be kalafungin (KAL 4) by its retention time, UV/vis spectrum, and HR/MS analysis using the authentic KAL 4 (Figure S4). As a putative native sugar acceptor for Med-8,14,29 KAL 4 was predicted to be a common intermediate in MED 1 and ACT 2 biosynthetic pathways (Figure 1).23,24,28 Dihydrokalafungin (DHK, 6), a dihydro form of KAL 4, was also produced and deduced by the retention time, UV/vis spectrum, and HR/MS analysis, which could be spontaneously converted from KAL 4 in ACT 2 pathway (Figure S4).23,24,28 These known compounds were derived from the med-8-deﬁcient med-cluster, and they were not detected in the host strain CH999 under current cultivating conditions (Figure 3B). which had been previously isolated from an engineered S. coelicolor strain.24 The retention time, UV/vis spectra, and HR/MS data indicative of molecular formula C21H21NO9S (molecular weight (MW) = 463) of 7 and 8 were conﬁrmed to be identical to those of authentic samples (Figure S8). In the ACT 2 biosynthetic pathway (Figure 1), the principal enzyme governing C-6 oxygenation is the ActVA-ORF5 (ﬂavin-dependent monooxygenase, FMO),24 which forms a two-component system (ActVA-ORF5/VB) in combination with the ActVB (Flavin:NADH oxidoreductase). This system has recently been demonstrated in vitro to catalyze an additional C-8 oxygenation (Figure 1).40 This study also that Med-7 (a C-6 FMO) solely aﬀords a showed40 trihydroxynaphthalene intermediate leading to DHK 6 (Figure 1). An S. coelicolor engineered strain in which the C-6 oxygenase genes were replaced with med-7 led to produce 7 and 8, together with KAL 4.24 This observation is reasonably explained by the monofunctionality at the C-6 oxygenation of Med-7 (Figure 1) to accumulate DHK 6, which is converted to its AcCys adducts as unwanted metabolites in the ACT pathway. A lactonizing conversion of DHK 6 to KAL 4 was demonstrated,40,41 indicating its mechanism is most likely via a hydroquinone formation (Figure S5).

The accumulation of DHK 6 and KAL 4 with the disappearance of MED 1 in the med-8-deﬁcient engineered strain (Figure 3B, CH999/pHSL3) supported that DHK 6 or KAL 4 is a key sugar acceptor, recognized by Med-8, and that Med-8 is essential for the formation of a C−C glycosidic bond between C-9 of the acceptor and C′-1 of NDP-angolasamine 5 (Figure 1). The biosynthesis of the glycosyl donor may be rate the biosynthesis of MED 1, as KAL 4 is limiting for occasionally accumulated together with MED 1 in the native strain AM-7161 (Figure 3B).29

The tailoring modiﬁcation at C-9 is a characteristic feature for the family of PNQ compounds. Besides a tailoring enzyme ActVA-ORF4 that was proved to be involved in the dimerization at C-9 for ACT 2,42 Med-8 is the second enzyme that can modify the C-9 position of PNQs, via C-glycosylation. Successful Construction and Expression of a Multi- gene C-Glycosylation Cassette pAYT55. Earlier studies demonstrated that the entire med cluster was expressed in a heterologous host (CH999/pIK340), strongly suggesting that the six ANG genes (med-14, -15, -16, -17, -18, and -20) on the med cluster biosynthesize a glucose to an NDP-angolasamine 5 in the MED biosynthesis.14 Here, to directly investigate their roles, we ﬁrst combined all six ANG genes with med-8 together into a transcriptional operon and put all of them in the downstream of a strong divergently paired promoter (PactIII/actI) to create an integrative plasmid pAYT55 (Figure S6). The expression of these seven genes on pAYT55 was controlled by the constitutive promoter (PactIII/actI), which is activated by a positive regulator ActII-ORF4 encoded by an R gene on pAYT55 (Figure 4A).39 pAYT55 was further introduced into the heterologous host CH999 strain that is unable to accumulate PNQ-related polyketides.43 qRT-PCR (real-time quantitative reverse transcription PCR) analysis revealed that the normal expression of the ﬁrst gene med-20 and last gene med-8, indicating the target transcriptional operon on pAYT55, could express eﬃciently in the recombinant strain CH999/ pAYT55 but not in the CH999 as a negative control (Figure 4B). Bioconversion of a PNQ Substrate into a C- Glycosylated Product using the Multigene Glycosyla- pubs.acs.org/acschemicalbiology

tion Cassette pAYT55. To check the eﬃcacy of this multigene glycosylation cassette to generate C-glycosylated the transformant of CH999/pAYT55 was compounds, subsequently cultivated in a liquid medium for feeding experiments. As shown in Figure 5, the supplementation of the predicted substrate KAL 4 into the CH999/pAYT55 culture resulted in a complete disappearance of KAL 4 and the detection of three related compounds: 4R-AcCys-DHK 7 and 4S-AcCys-DHK 8, which can be converted from KAL 4 previously in the ACT 2 pathway (Figure 5A),22−24,28 and compound 9 (Figure S7−S9). In contrast, feeding KAL 4 to CH999 only led to an accumulation of 4R-AcCys-DHK 7 and 4S-AcCys-DHK 8. Meanwhile, these data demonstrated that the conversion of KAL 4 into two AcCys adducts (7 and 8) and DHK 6 in CH999 is independent of ACT 2 or MED 1 pathways, but was caused by the host CH999. And pAYT55 is essential for the appearance of compound 9 when fed with KAL 4. the puriﬁed compound 9 in deuterated dimethyl sulfoxide (DMSO-d6) suggested the labile property of 9 (data not shown). An LC/MS analysis of the recovered NMR sample of 9 revealed the almost spontaneous complete in vitro conversion of 9 into MED 1 in DMSO (Figures S7 and S9). Thus, formula of compound 9 was deduced to be C24H29NO8 (calcd 460.1971 for [M + H]+, observed as 460.1979), corresponding to dihydromedermycin (DHM, 9) (Figure S7), the structure of which was conﬁrmed by an LC/HRMS analysis and comparison of UV/vis spectra.

DHM 9 was solely derived from KAL 4 fed into the culture, as it was not detected in a control experiment CH999 fed by DMSO (Figure 5A). The host CH999 strain fed with KAL 4 produced DHK 6 and its AcCys adducts 7 and 8, indicating that the CH999 retains the converting activity of a PNQ lactone to its corresponding carboxylic acid (dihydro form, Figure 5A).

At the presence of the glycosylation cassette carried by pAYT55, KAL 4 feed was eﬃciently converted into a C- glycosylated product DHM 9 together with 7 and 8 (Figure 5A). On the one hand, one explanation is that DHK 6 converted in vivo from KAL 4 was subjected to Med-8 as an acceptor substrate for the production of C-glycosylated DHM 9 (Figure 5B). On the other hand, an engineered CH999 strain carrying the entire med-cluster (CH999/pIK340) produced MED 1 instead of DHM 9 (Figure 3B), suggesting the most eﬃcient control on the conversion of the dihydro form to the lactone by a separate enzyme in the last stage of MED 1 biosynthesis. Although the combined results are unable to specify the true sugar acceptor, either DHK 6 or KAL 4, the ANG C-glycosylation activity of Med-8 was rigorously proved. The native producer AM-7161 was found to produce MED 1 but no DHM 9.29 However, S. coelicolor can accumulate three forms of ACT 2, which diﬀer at two C-4/C-1 positions of the dimer (ACT, γ-ACT, and γ′-ACT).44 Interestingly, during the puriﬁcation of DHM 9, we found that DHM 9 is able to be converted in vitro into MED 1 completely and spontaneously when it was kept at room temperature (RT) and in air, but no reverse conversion was detected (Figure S9), suggesting that the conversion in vitro from DHM 9 (the dihydro form of MED 1) into MED 1 (lactonization at C-4/C-1) is an enzymatic-independent process. Altogether, this study characterized the essential function of Med-8 involved in C-glycosylation in MED 1 biosynthesis. https://doi.org/10.1021/acschembio.1c00227 ACS Chem. Biol. 2021, 16, 1059−1069

Diﬀerent from UrdGT2 and SsfS6 catalyzing attachment of NDP-activated olivose to angucycline and tetracycline accept- ors, respectively,8,9,32,36 Med-8 acts as the ﬁrst example of deoxyaminosugar C-GT for a deoxyaminosugar transfer. To our knowledge, as the ﬁrst report, the establishment of a deoxyaminosugar-C-glycosylation cassette (pAYT55) and feeding experiments here further proved the capability of C- glycosylation of Med-8 as a C-GT for attaching a deoxyaminosugar ANG 5 into an aromatic polyketide aglycone and the suﬃcient roles of this cassette for the biosynthesis of ANG 5. The availability of this sugar C-glycosylation cassette opens up a possibility to generate C-glycosylated compounds with pharmaceutical potentials and might allow further development of Streptomyces recombinants for combinatorial biosynthesis of both “unnatural” and natural products with enhanced biological activities. Therefore, this study will have a signiﬁcant impact on the understanding and engineering of structural modiﬁcations of a variety of aromatic compounds.

Strains, Plasmids, and Reagents Used in This Work. S. coelicolor CH999 (CH999) (proA1 argA1 redE60 Δact::ermE, SCP1− SCP2−) does not produce PNQ-related products and was used as a host the heterologous expression of medermycin-biosynthetic genes.43 Escherichia coli DH5α was used for routine DNA manipulations. E. coli 25113/pIJ790 was a host for PCR-mediated gene inactivation with Redirect technology,45,46 and E. coli ET12567/pUZ8002 (dam− dcm− hsdS) was used for intergeneric conjugation.39 pT7Blue, pBluescript II SK(+) (pBS in short), and pSET151 were obtained from Novagen for PCR cloning or subcloning. pWHM4* containing the ermE* promoter (PermE)39 was used for the expression of med-8. pIK340 carrying the entire med gene cluster14 was used as a template for the ampliﬁcation of med-8 and technology.45,46 pIJ773, also for med-8 inactivation by Redirect carrying an apramycin-resistance cassette (aac(3)IV), was the template for the ampliﬁcation of the reporter expression cassette referenced in the Redirect technology. pSET152 and pNEB193J were used for the multi-med-gene coexpression plasmid.39 For feeding experiments, KAL 4 was isolated from S. tanashiensis JCM4086 and S. coelicolor B22.22,23

Culture Conditions and General Genetic Manipulations. E. coli strains were incubated on Luria broth (LB) agar or liquid medium, while Streptomyces strains were cultivated on R4 agar medium and grown in tryptic soy broth (TSB), or R5MS liquid medium.22,39 When needed, antibiotics were added at ﬁnal concentrations of 25 μg/mL for chloramphenicol and kanamycin, 25 μg/mL for apramycin, and 100 μg/mL for ampicillin. Standard methods to handle E. coli and Streptomyces in vivo and in vitro, such as plasmid DNA preparation, restriction digestion, gel electrophoresis, ligation reactions, Streptomyces genomic DNA isolation, protoplast transformation, intergeneric conjugation, and so on, were carried out according to the procedures described previously.39 The PCR ampliﬁcation was performed with KOD-Plus-DNA polymerase (Toyobo). PCR primers used in this study were listed in Table S1. Bioinformatic Analysis. The sequence alignment between Med-8 and its homologues was conducted using the Clustal X program (version 2). The phylogenetic tree was established based on the sequence alignment using distance/neighbor-joining programs with the Poisson correction distance model in the MEGA X software package. The interior branch length supports were from 1000 replicates. The conserved domain and similarity searches were conducted using the online programs of CDD (http://www.ncbi. nlm.nih.gov/Structure/cdd/wrpsb.cgi), BLAST (http://blast.ncbi. nlm.nih.gov/Blast.cgi), and STRING (ver. 9.05) (http://string905. embl.de). The structural modeling of Med-8 was performed using PyMOL (http://www.pymol.org/) and UrdGT2 as a reference protein template (PDB ID: 2P6P) from S. f radiae. pubs.acs.org/acschemicalbiology

In-Frame Inactivation of med-8 in the Entire med Gene Cluster. The entire med cluster carried by pIK340 was proved to be functional for MED 1 production in CH999 (CH999/pIK340).14 Inactivation of med-8 in the med cluster was conducted by PCR- mediated Redirect technology on pIK340.45,46 The 1.4 kb apramycin- resistance cassette (aac(3)IV) was ampliﬁed from pIJ773 using two long primers (Red8S/Red8A) listed in Table S1 and delivered into pIK340-containing E. coli BW25113/pIJ790 to replace med-8 through a homologous recombination. The resultant plasmid carrying the engineered mutant med gene cluster was designated as pHSL3. The substitution of med-8 with the reporter cassette (aac(3)IV) on pHSL3 was conﬁrmed by PCR (primers listed in Table S1). pHSL3 was then introduced into CH999 to yield a med-8-deﬁcient mutant strain CH999/pHSL3. Complementary Expression of med-8. Gene med-8 with its native ribosomal binding site was ampliﬁed by PCR from pIK340 using a pair of primers (XF1A and XF1B, Table S1). The ampliﬁed med-8 was inserted between the XbaI and EcoRI sites of pT7Blue for sequencing. After it was recovered from pT7Blue, the med-8 was ligated with pWHM4*, generating pHSL5. Subsequently, pHSL5 was delivered into CH999/pHSL3 by a protoplast transformation to yield a med-8-complementary strain CH999/(pHSL3+pHSL5).

Metabolic Analysis of med-8-Deﬁcient Mutant and Com- plementary Strains. Spores of several Streptomyces strains (CH999, CH999/pIK340, CH999/pHSL3, and CH999/(pHSL3+pHSL5)) were grown on R4 agar medium for 4−5 d at 30 °C for the observation of red-brown pigmentation indicating MED 1 production (Figure 3).39 The spores of these strains on R4 agar medium were collected and inoculated into 10 mL of TSB medium, respectively, and cultivated on a shaker (200 rpm) at 30 °C for 2 d. Then, 2 mL of the resultant seed cultures were transferred into 100 mL of R5MS medium for continuing cultivation on a shaker (200 rpm) at 30 °C for 5 d.39 After centrifugation, supernatants were subjected to an LC/ESI- time-of-ﬂight (TOF)-MS analysis on the system of Waters, Alliance HT equipped with LCT-Premier using a column (TOSOH ODS- 100S, 4.6 × 150 mm) under the following analytic conditions: column temperature: 40 °C; solvent A: H2O + 0.1% HCOOH; solvent B: CH3CN + 0.1% HCOOH; gradient proﬁle: 0−35 min, 10−95% B; 35−40 min, 95% B; 40−45 min, 95−10% B; ﬂow rate: 1.0 mL/min. Detection at 420 nm, MS: LCT-premier (Waters), ESI-(±).

Construction of a Multi-med-Gene Coexpression System as a C-Glycosylation Cassette. Five segments covering totally six contiguous genes (med-14, -15, -16, -17, -18, and -20) and med-8 were obtained ﬁrst by PCR ampliﬁcation and subcloning, respectively, then ligated together by the step-cloning strategy using pT7 Blue, pBluescript II SK (+) (pBS), or pNEB193J.39 The resultant multigene expression cassette was ﬁnally transferred from the vector pNEB193J into pSET152 to yield an integrative expression plasmid designated as pAYT55. Feeding Experiments using the Multigene Coexpression System (pAYT55) for Bioconversion. pAYT55 was introduced into CH999 by intergeneric conjugation to generate a recombinant strain CH999/pAYT55. Spores of CH999 and CH999/pAYT55 strains were incubated in seed cultures and transferred into 100 mL of R5MS medium for 2 d of continuous cultivation as description as above. After they were fed with 1.0 mg of KAL 4, the cultures were cultivated further for 3 d. The supernatants of all cultures after centrifugation at 16 100g for 5 min were directly subjected to an LC/ ESI-TOF-MS analysis under the conditions as described above.

Puriﬁcation and Structural Elucidation of Dihydromeder- mycin (DHM, 9) Produced in Feeding Experiments. Spores of CH999/pAYT55 were inoculated in 10 mL of TSB medium and cultivated on a shaker (200 rpm) at 30 °C for 2 d. The seed cultures were transferred into 1 L of R5MS medium distributed equally to 10 Erlenmyer ﬂasks (100 mL/ﬂask) for feeding experiments with KAL 4 (1 mg/ﬂask). The supernatants were harvested by centrifugation and adjusted to pH 7.0. Then 30 mL of the supernatant was applied to an octadecylsilyl (ODS) cartridge (SepPak vac 6 cm3, Waters) equilibrated with water. After the resin was washed with 15 mL of 15% aqueous acetonitrile containing 0.1% formic acid, the compounds https://doi.org/10.1021/acschembio.1c00227 ACS Chem. Biol. 2021, 16, 1059−1069

were eluted with 10 mL of methanol. All of the supernatant was treated in this procedure, and the eluent was collected and dried in vacuo. The resulting extract was puriﬁed by preparative HPLC using a column (TOSOH ODS-100S, 7.8 × 300 mm) under the following conditions: column temperature: 50 °C; solvent A: H2O containing 0.1% formic acid; solvent B: CH3CN containing 0.1% formic acid; gradient proﬁle: 0−10 min, 20−32% B, 10−15 min, 32−95% B; 15− 20 min, 95% B; 20−25 min, 95−20% B; ﬂow rate: 2.0 mL/min. The isolated yield of DHM 9 was 5.1 mg. The molecular formula of 9 was deduced by an HR-ESI-MS analysis as C24H29NO8 (calcd 460.1971 for [M + H]+, found 460.1979). NMR measurements of DHM 9 in DMSO-d6 suggested the labile property of 9 (data not shown). An LCMS analysis of the recovered NMR sample revealed the almost complete conversion of 9 into MED 1 (Figures S7 and S9).

Expression Detection of C-Glycosylation Genes in the Multigene Coexpression System (CH999/pAYT55) by qRT- PCR. The extraction of total RNA from Streptomyces mycelia (CH999/pAYT55 and CH999) was performed using a Quick RNA isolation kit (BioTeke Corporation) according to the manufacturer’s protocol. The total RNA isolated from CH999 acted as a negative control. The concentrations of total RNA were measured on a NanoDrop ND1000 Spectrophotometer (NanoDrop Technologie). The total cDNA was obtained via a reverse transcription using a PrimeScript RT reagent Kit with gDNA Eraser (Perfect Real Time) (TaKaRa) and following the manufacturer’s protocols. Afterward, a qRT-PCR analysis using cDNA as a template was conducted using the SYBR Premix Ex TaqTM II Kit (TaKaRa) on an Applied Biosystems Quant Studio 3 Real-Time PCR System (Applied Biosystems). Primers speciﬁc for several glycosylation genes in CH999/pAYT55 were synthesized by Sangon Biotech (Shanghai) Co., Ltd. The housekeeping gene (hrd) acted as a positive control. The 2−ΔΔCT method was used to analyze the relative changes in gene expression.47 The experiment was performed in triplicate. *sı Supporting Information The Supporting Information is available free of charge at https://pubs.acs.org/doi/10.1021/acschembio.1c00227.
